<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-339-497  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 339 497.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 30 1989 n523 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computers still the plum of the economy. (Computer and BusinessEquipment Manufacturers Association report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Revenues in 1988 for the US computer and business equipmentindustry rose an estimated 11.6 percent over 1987 but for thefirst time failed to keep pace with overall business spending onmachinery and equipment, which was up an estimated 14.7 percentdue to heavy export demands.andP;  The estimates come from the Computerand Business Equipment Manufacturing Assn (CBEMA), whichanticipates a slowing of the revenue growth rates in 1989 as theUS falls into an economic downturn or even recession.andP;  CBEMAbelieves that in the long run, however, the computer, businessequipment and telecommunications industries in terms of overallcombined revenue will increase their share of the gross nationalproduct from 8.7 percent or $423.7 billion in 1988 to 10.1 percentor $864 billion by 1998.andP;  Computer and related equipment revenuesrose an estimated 11 percent to $131.4 billion in 1988.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryEconomicsFinancial AnalysisReportsForecastingRevenueGrowthComputer and Business Equipment Manufacturers AssociationMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Projected revenues: U.S. telecommunications industry. (graph)Projected revenue growth: U.S. computer and business equipmentindustry. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>